    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under ASC 860, an assignment (pledging) of receivables is a secured borrowing, NOT a sale. The receivables remain on the assignor's balance sheet as collateral. The cash received from the lender is recorded as a loan payable (Notes Payable — Assigned Receivables). Collections from the assigned receivables are used to repay the loan, plus interest and service fees. The assignor must disclose: (1) the amount of receivables assigned, (2) the terms of the assignment. If the debtor defaults on the receivables, the lender has recourse to the assignor (with-recourse) or may bear the loss (without-recourse, which may qualify as a sale).",
