      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - A repurchase agreement where the repurchase price exceeds the original selling price indicates the seller retains control of the asset. This is essentially a loan, with the difference representing interest expense over the term of the agreement.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - A consignment arrangement involves one party (the consignor) entrusting goods to another party (the consignee) for sale, with the consignor retaining ownership until the goods are sold to a third party. This scenario involves a guaranteed repurchase, not a consignment.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Recognizing revenue of $100,000 would be appropriate if a sale had occurred, but the repurchase agreement indicates the seller retains control. A repurchase liability is recognized, but not in conjunction with revenue recognition.",
