    options: ["No adjustment needed — the transfer was at book value","Increase consolidated depreciation expense by $3,333 (to depreciate at original basis: $60,000/6 = $10,000 vs. $80,000/6 = $13,333, difference is additional depreciation needed)","Decrease depreciation by $3,333 to reflect the original cost basis","Increase depreciation by $6,667"],
    correctAnswer: 2,
    explanation: "From the consolidated entity's perspective, no sale occurred — the asset should remain at its original basis: Cost $100,000, Accum. Dep. $40,000, NBV $60,000. Subsidiary records: Cost $80,000, depreciated over 6 years = $13,333/year. Consolidated depreciation should be: $60,000 ÷ 6 = $10,000/year. Adjustment: DECREASE consolidated depreciation by $3,333 ($13,333 − $10,000). The $20,000 gain on the intercompany sale ($80,000 − $60,000 NBV) is eliminated in consolidation. Over 6 years, the $20,000 gain is realized through $3,333/year lower depreciation, ultimately bringing the total depreciation back in line.",
