      2: "Why option C is WRONG - One of the main benefits of the shortcut method is that, when applicable, ongoing effectiveness testing is *not* required. The assumption of perfect effectiveness eliminates the need for reassessment.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The shortcut method assumes *perfect* offset, not just a partial offset like 50%. A partial offset would indicate hedge ineffectiveness, which is not allowed under the shortcut method.",
