    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "The conventional retail method (also called the lower of cost or market retail method) excludes net markdowns from the denominator when calculating the cost-to-retail ratio. By excluding markdowns from the retail column, the denominator is larger, resulting in a lower cost-to-retail percentage. When this lower percentage is applied to ending inventory at retail, it produces a lower inventory value — approximating lower of cost or market. If markdowns were included, the ratio would be higher (the average cost method), and the result would be closer to average cost.",
