    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under ASC 715-60, OPEB accounting follows a similar framework to pension accounting (service cost, interest cost, amortization of prior service cost, gains/losses) but differs in key ways: (1) OPEB plans are typically unfunded (no plan assets), so the full obligation appears as a liability; (2) the obligation is measured using the accumulated postretirement benefit obligation (APBO) rather than PBO; (3) APBO reflects the attribution of benefits to service periods up to the full eligibility date; (4) healthcare cost trend rates are a critical assumption unique to OPEB. The funded status (APBO minus plan assets) is recognized on the balance sheet.",
