    topic: "Derivatives and Hedging",
    subtopic: "Derivative Definition",
    difficulty: "easy",
    skillLevel: "Remembering and Understanding",
    question: "Under ASC 815, a derivative instrument has all of the following characteristics EXCEPT:",
    options: ["It has one or more underlyings and one or more notional amounts","It requires a large initial net investment relative to the exposure","It requires no initial net investment or a smaller net investment than would be required for other contracts with similar exposure","It can be net settled"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "ASC 815-10-15-83 defines a derivative as having three characteristics: (1) one or more underlyings (price, rate, index) and one or more notional amounts (units, shares, bushels) or payment provisions; (2) requires no initial net investment or an initial net investment smaller than would be required for contracts with the same response to market factors; (3) terms require or permit net settlement (can be settled net, there is a market mechanism for net settlement, or the asset delivered is readily convertible to cash). A derivative specifically does NOT require a large initial investment — that would be a characteristic of the underlying asset itself.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Derivatives are based on underlying assets and involve notional amounts to determine the payoff, so this is a characteristic of a derivative.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - Derivatives require little to no initial investment, distinguishing them from traditional assets that require a substantial upfront investment. A large initial investment is characteristic of the underlying asset, not the derivative.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Derivatives are designed to provide exposure to price movements with minimal upfront cost, making this a key characteristic of a derivative instrument.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The ability to net settle is a core feature of derivatives, allowing parties to settle the net gain or loss without exchanging the underlying asset itself.",
    },
    educational: "Derivatives derive their value from an underlying asset, index, or rate. They are used for hedging risk, speculation, or gaining exposure to an asset without owning it directly. Because of their nature, derivatives require little or no initial investment, allowing for leveraged positions.",
    examTip: "When identifying derivatives, focus on the minimal initial investment and the reliance on an underlying asset's price movement.",
    memoryAid: "NINJA: No Initial Net Investment, Just Assets (Underlying)",
    reference: "ASC 815-10-15-83",
