    question: "A company has a legal obligation to decommission a plant at the end of its 20-year useful life. The estimated future cost is $5,000,000 and the credit-adjusted risk-free rate is 5%. The PV of $1 at 5% for 20 years is 0.37689. What is the initial ARO and how does it affect depreciation?",
    options: ["ARO of $5,000,000; depreciation increases by $250,000/year","ARO of $1,884,450; the same amount is added to the carrying value of the plant and depreciated over 20 years ($94,223/year)","ARO of $1,884,450; no effect on depreciation","No ARO is recorded because the obligation is 20 years away"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under ASC 410-20-25, an ARO is recognized at fair value (present value) when incurred if a reasonable estimate can be made. Initial measurement: $5,000,000 × 0.37689 = $1,884,450. The corresponding amount is added to the carrying amount of the related long-lived asset and depreciated over its useful life: $1,884,450 ÷ 20 = $94,223/year additional depreciation. The ARO liability is accreted each period using the credit-adjusted risk-free rate (5%), increasing the liability toward the $5,000,000 settlement amount over 20 years. Accretion expense is classified as an operating expense.",
