      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - When an exchange has commercial substance, the new asset is recorded at the fair value of the asset given up. This reflects the economic reality of the transaction and ensures that gains and losses are properly recognized.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - The original cost of the old equipment ($100,000) is used to calculate book value and any gain or loss on the exchange, but it's not the basis for recording the new asset's value when commercial substance exists.",
