    educational: "Exchanges of nonmonetary assets are classified as having commercial substance if the future cash flows of the entity are expected to change as a result of the transaction. When commercial substance exists, gains and losses are recognized immediately, reflecting the economic reality of the exchange. The new asset is recorded at the fair value of what was given up.",
    examTip: "Always determine if an exchange has commercial substance first; this dictates whether you use fair value or book value to record the new asset.",
    memoryAid: "Commercial Substance = Fair Value (CS = FV)",
