    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "ASU 2020-06 simplified the accounting for convertible instruments by eliminating the beneficial conversion feature (BCF) model and the cash conversion feature model. Under the simplified guidance, most convertible debt instruments are accounted for as a single liability at amortized cost, unless they: (1) contain an embedded derivative that requires bifurcation, (2) are issued at a substantial premium, or (3) are in the scope of ASC 815 (derivatives). This means the conversion feature is no longer separately valued in equity, resulting in lower interest expense and higher reported debt.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - ASU 2020-06 eliminated the requirement to bifurcate convertible bonds that do not require cash settlement into debt and equity components. The entire instrument is now generally treated as debt.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - ASU 2020-06 simplifies the accounting for convertible debt by treating most instruments as a single liability measured at amortized cost. This eliminates the need to separately value the conversion feature and recognize it as equity, unless specific exceptions apply.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Convertible debt contains a debt component, representing the issuer's obligation to repay the principal. It cannot be accounted for entirely as equity unless it meets the definition of equity under other accounting standards.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - While some financial instruments are measured at fair value through net income, convertible debt that falls under the scope of ASU 2020-06 and does not require cash settlement is generally measured at amortized cost, not fair value.",
    },
    educational: "ASU 2020-06 aimed to reduce the complexity and cost of accounting for convertible instruments. By eliminating the beneficial conversion feature and cash conversion feature models, the standard simplifies the accounting for these instruments, making financial statements easier to understand and more comparable.",
    examTip: "Focus on the exceptions to the ASU 2020-06 guidance, such as embedded derivatives requiring bifurcation, instruments issued at a substantial premium, and those within the scope of ASC 815, as these are common areas for exam questions.",
    memoryAid: "Think: 'ASU 2020-06: Single & Simple' - meaning most convertible bonds are now accounted for as a single liability, simplifying the process.",
    reference: "ASU 2020-06; ASC 470-20",
