    explanation: "A stock split increases the number of shares outstanding and proportionally decreases the par value per share, with no change in total equity. After a 2-for-1 split: shares increase from 100,000 to 200,000, par value decreases from $10 to $5. Total par value remains $1,000,000. No journal entry is required — only a memorandum entry noting the change. This differs from a large stock dividend, which requires a debit to retained earnings. Stock splits do not change stockholders' equity components.",
