    whyWrong: {
      0: "Option A is WRONG because it incorrectly includes the direct acquisition costs ($200,000) as part of the consideration transferred. Acquisition costs are expensed, not capitalized as part of the acquisition.",
      1: "Option B is CORRECT because it accurately sums the cash paid ($5,000,000), the fair value of the stock issued ($3,000,000), and the fair value of the contingent consideration ($500,000). Acquisition costs are expensed separately and do not affect the consideration transferred.",
      2: "Option C is WRONG because it subtracts an amount from the correct consideration, likely due to confusion about the treatment of acquisition costs or contingent consideration.",
      3: "Option D is WRONG because it only considers the cash portion of the consideration and fails to include the fair value of the stock issued and the contingent consideration.",
    },
    educational: "In a business combination, the acquirer records the assets acquired and liabilities assumed at their fair values. The consideration transferred includes cash, equity interests, and contingent consideration measured at fair value on the acquisition date. Direct acquisition costs are expensed as incurred, which is a key difference from asset acquisitions.",
    examTip: "Remember to expense acquisition-related costs in a business combination; they are not included in the consideration transferred or the cost of the acquired assets.",
    memoryAid: "Think 'BEC': Business combination Expenses are Current-period expenses.",
    reference: "ASC 805-30-30-7; ASC 805-10-25-23",
