    educational: "Debt covenants protect lenders, and violating them usually makes the debt immediately due. However, if the lender provides a waiver extending beyond one year from the balance sheet date, the debt can be classified as noncurrent, reflecting the lender's temporary relinquishment of their right to demand immediate payment. This treatment acknowledges the practical reality of the situation and provides a more accurate picture of the company's financial obligations.",
    examTip: "Focus on the *length* of the waiver period from the balance sheet date; if it's more than a year, the debt can be noncurrent.",
    memoryAid: "Think 'Waiver Length Matters': The *length* of the waiver determines the debt classification.",
