    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Units-of-production depreciation: Depreciable base = Cost − Salvage = $400,000 − $40,000 = $360,000. Per-unit rate = $360,000 ÷ 180,000 units = $2.00 per unit. Year 1 depreciation = 30,000 units × $2.00 = $60,000. This method is appropriate when the asset's usefulness is more closely related to use (production) than to the passage of time. It results in a variable depreciation charge each year based on actual output. Examples include mining equipment, delivery vehicles (miles-driven basis), and manufacturing machinery.",
