    question: "On January 1, 2024, Miller Corp. entered into a 5-year lease for equipment. The present value of the lease payments is $800,000. The equipment's useful life is 8 years. Miller does not obtain ownership of the asset at the end of the lease term. The equipment has no alternative use to the lessor at the end of the lease. Miller's incremental borrowing rate is 6%. The lessor's implicit rate, which Miller is aware of, is 5%. How should Miller classify this lease?",
    options: ["Finance lease.","Operating lease.","Sale-type lease.","Direct financing lease."],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "The lease should be classified as a finance lease because the present value of the lease payments ($800,000) is greater than 90% of the fair value of the asset. Since fair value isn't given, we can assume that the fair value is close to the PV of lease payments. Also, the lease has no alternative use to the lessor. This meets the criteria for a finance lease under ASC 842.",
    whyWrong: {
      1: "An operating lease classification would be incorrect because the present value of the lease payments is a substantial portion of the asset's fair value, and the equipment has no alternative use to the lessor.",
      2: "Sale-type and direct financing leases are lessor classifications, not lessee classifications.",
      3: "Sale-type and direct financing leases are lessor classifications, not lessee classifications.",
    },
    educational: "A lessee classifies a lease as either a finance lease or an operating lease. If any of the following criteria are met, the lease is classified as a finance lease: (1) transfer of ownership, (2) purchase option the lessee is reasonably certain to exercise, (3) the lease term is for the major part of the remaining economic life of the underlying asset, (4) the present value of the sum of the lease payments equals or exceeds substantially all of the fair value of the underlying asset, or (5) the underlying asset is of such a specialized nature that it is expected to have no alternative use to the lessor at the end of the lease term.",
    examTip: "Focus on the lease classification criteria. If any of the criteria are met, it's a finance lease. If none are met, it's an operating lease. Remember to differentiate between lessee and lessor accounting.",
    memoryAid: "For lessee accounting, remember the acronym 'OWNS' (Ownership transfer, Written purchase option likely, Ninety percent or more of asset's fair value, Substantially all of the asset's economic life) to help recall the finance lease criteria.",
    reference: "ASC 842",
