    skillLevel: "Remembering and Understanding",
    question: "Zenith Corp. identified a tax position related to the deductibility of executive compensation. Zenith believes there is a 60% probability that the tax position will be sustained based solely on its technical merits if challenged by the taxing authority. If the tax position is challenged, Zenith estimates that it will incur $50,000 in legal fees. The potential tax benefit of the position is $200,000. Using the cumulative probability approach, what is the amount of the tax benefit that Zenith should recognize?",
    options: ["$0","$80,000","$120,000","$200,000"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "Under ASC 740, an entity can only recognize the benefit of a tax position if it is more likely than not (a greater than 50% likelihood) that the position will be sustained upon examination by the taxing authorities. Since there is only a 60% probability that the tax position will be sustained, the \"more likely than not\" threshold is met. However, the amount recognized is based on the largest amount of benefit that is greater than 50% likely of being realized upon ultimate settlement. Since the probability is 60% that the full $200,000 tax benefit will be realized, and this is the only probability provided, $200,000 multiplied by 60% is $120,000. The expense to defend the tax position is not considered when measuring the benefit to be recognized. If the more likely than not threshold is not met, no benefit is recognized.",
