    question: "On January 1, 2024, Gamma Corp. sold a building with a carrying amount of $800,000 to Delta Leasing for $1,200,000. Gamma immediately leased the building back under a 10-year lease with annual payments of $158,254, payable at the beginning of each year. The building's remaining useful life is 20 years. Gamma's incremental borrowing rate is 6%, which is readily available, and the implicit rate is not readily determinable by Gamma. What amount of profit should Gamma recognize from the sale portion of the sale-leaseback transaction in 2024, assuming the lease is classified as an operating lease?",
    options: ["$0","$400,000","$200,000","$100,000"],
    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "The lease is classified as an operating lease since the present value of the lease payments is less than 90% of the fair value of the asset. (158,254*7.36009 = $1,164,809 which is less than $1,200,000*90% = $1,080,000). Since the lease is an operating lease, the profit on the sale should be deferred to the extent that the sales price exceeds the fair value. The amount of deferred profit is then amortized over the lease term. The excess gain is $1,200,000 - $800,000 = $400,000. Because the asset's fair value is assumed to be $1,200,000 since this is the sales price, the entire profit is recognized. However, since the lease is an operating lease, the profit is limited to the amount where the sales price exceeds fair value. There is no excess since sales price = fair value. Thus, the entire gain is deferred. Because the lease is an operating lease, the profit is amortized over the lease term. $400,000/10 years = $40,000. So, the profit recognized will be the amount exceeding what is amortized, which means the remaining gain, $400,000 - $40,000 amortized during the year = $360,000, is deferred. The annual payments start at the beginning of the year. The present value factor of annuity due is 7.36009 for 10 years at 6%. Since the present value of the lease payments does not exceed 90% of the fair value, the lease is an operating lease (as indicated). The profit should be recognized to the extent that it exceeds the present value of the lease payments. Since the fair value of the asset is $1,200,000 and the PV of lease payments is $1,164,809, $1,200,000-$1,164,809 = $35,191 should be recognized immediately. After which, $400,000 - $35,191 = $364,809 is deferred and amortized over the lease term. \n\nHowever, if the lease payments comprise a major part of the asset's fair value, but not substantially all, then the seller-lessee will only recognize any profit that is more than the present value of the minimum lease payments. This means that if the present value of the minimum lease payments is $1,164,809.14, then the profit recognized on the sale is $400,000 - ($1,200,000 - $1,164,809.14) = $364,809.14. $364,809.14 is deferred and amortized over the lease term. $364,809.14/10 = $36,481. Thus, $364,809.14 - $36,481 = $328,328 is deferred. The profit recognized is $36,481 + $35,191 = $71,672. (ASC 842)",
